  "2026-07-10T21:41:16.024Z",maintainer-agent,"Decision-point-3 input (2026-07-10 planning pass): pm-dfg0 now carries a grounded S1-S4 scoping note with the verified current pagination surface (list --limit/--offset unbounded-by-default; search --limit only; context --depth full = MAX_SAFE_INTEGER hole; no cursor anywhere). Recommendation from that analysis: cursor tokens over offset (opaque stable-sort-tuple cursor, id tiebreak) — offset re-scans degrade at 100k+ and break under concurrent mutation; a threshold-gated default limit preserves small-workspace ergonomics (pm-z436). The S1 cursor primitive can be spiked in the pm-rjqr SDK query facade as ADR input before this ADR formally lands."
  "2026-07-11T10:38:42.909Z",maintainer-agent,"Decision inputs from the 2026-07-11 perf brainstorm (ledger on pm-9rxu):\n- Option 1 (read index) gains a maintenance-strategy sub-decision: incremental index updates riding the existing mutation path (same hook family as background semantic refresh — write-time O(1) upkeep) vs rebuild-on-stale-read. Invalidation source candidate: mtime/stat journal, same keying the shipped three-tier metadata cache (ADR pm-vnie) already trusts.\n- Any embedded store (SQLite/LanceDB-adjacent) stays a gitignored, rebuildable CACHE — never authoritative (ADR pm-i7i4). Rebuild cost at 1M items is itself a budgeted number (mi2x tier reports).\n- Startup is near-floor (bundle + lazy imports + compile cache + lazy activation all shipped), so this ADR's read-path options carry the remaining order-of-magnitude; git-subprocess count on read paths is a fifth decision driver worth stating explicitly (pure reads may need zero git spawns)."
close_reason: "Accepted scale-out ADR: rebuildable SDK-first read index, format-versioned fan-out, cursor/bounded-output contract, sharded claim locking, and Git/history growth policy; grounded in local 100k benchmark evidence."
body: "## Context\n\nThe existing three-tier metadata cache (pm-vnie) avoids reparsing unchanged item files, but every cold CLI process still enumerates and stats every item. The local scale harness (pm-mi2x) measures this at 100,000 items: CLI list/search/next take about 28-32 seconds; warm SDK reads take 3-8 seconds; next emits 126k-192k estimated tokens. The Git-native working tree remains authoritative per pm-i7i4.\n\n## Decision\n\n### 1. Derived read index and invalidation\n\nExtend the existing runtime metadata-cache family into a versioned derived read index under `.agents/pm/runtime/`; do not introduce a database, server, or daemon. The index stores light metadata projections, stable ordering tuples, dependency edges, claim/actionability fields, source paths/formats, a context fingerprint, and per-type-directory generation signatures. Bodies and heavy collections remain separate opt-in tiers.\n\nNormal reads may take an O(result) fast path when the index version, context fingerprint, item-directory signatures, and mutation generation agree. All pm writes use atomic replacement, so creates, deletes, moves, migrations, and mutations change a directory signature and invalidate the fast path. A stale, absent, corrupt, version-mismatched, or extension-hook-incompatible index transparently falls back to the canonical source scan and rebuilds the index. `pm reindex`, strict validation, repair, migration, and explicit cache-bypass paths always retain a source-scan mode. Direct edits to `.agents/pm` are outside the supported mutation contract; users must use pm mutations or `pm reindex` after such recovery edits.\n\nIndex maintenance must not create a singleton write bottleneck. Writes append bounded, atomic delta records or invalidate a generation marker while holding only the existing per-item lock; a compaction/rebuild folds deltas into immutable index snapshots. A crash can lose derived deltas, never source data: signature/generation mismatch forces rebuild.\n\n### 2. Item-directory fan-out and format migration\n\nFlat type directories remain readable. The scale layout uses deterministic two-level hash buckets derived from the normalized item id under each type folder. The storage `format_version` gates writes; migrations are lossless, resumable, lock-aware, and dual-read old/new layouts until completion. History and per-item locks use the same id-derived fan-out independently. No layout migration is implicit during an ordinary read.\n\n### 3. Bounded output and cursor pagination\n\nUse opaque, versioned base64url cursors over a stable ordering tuple plus id tiebreaker and a fingerprint of the normalized query/filter/sort contract. Cursor mismatch is an actionable error; offset remains a compatibility alias but is not the scale contract. Result envelopes expose `has_more`, `next_cursor`, applied limit, and total only when it is available without an extra full scan.\n\nSmall workspaces preserve current defaults. At the documented scale threshold, list/search/context/next apply a bounded default chosen to keep the normal agent payload below 5,000 estimated tokens, with an explicit truncation marker and continuation hint. Explicit `--limit`, `--all`, or full-depth compatibility controls remain available so no capability is removed.\n\n### 4. Claim and lock scaling\n\nPer-item locks remain the atomic test-and-set boundary and naturally shard by id. Claim-next walks bounded cursor pages and retries after a race loss. Singleton settings/session operations use their existing dedicated locks with bounded jitter; neither index reads nor index delta writes acquire one global workspace lock.\n\n### 5. Git and history growth\n\nDerived runtime indexes, benchmark fixtures, and reports generated outside committed docs stay gitignored. Canonical item/history files remain reviewable. `pm history-compact --all-over` is the supported checkpoint/prune mechanism; scale guidance will recommend an event/byte threshold and advisory `git gc`/maintenance cadence, but pm will not run destructive Git maintenance automatically. Archival of terminal items requires a separate format-versioned, reversible feature and is not part of read-index correctness.\n\n## Consequences\n\n- CLI, SDK, MCP, and packages share one SDK-first query/index contract.\n- Correctness never depends on a derived store, and source-scan equivalence tests remain mandatory.\n- Successful hot reads perform no Git subprocess and no O(workspace) item stat walk.\n- Writes stay O(1) with per-item contention; occasional rebuild cost is measured locally at 10k/100k/1M.\n- Cursor tokens are stable for an unchanged query generation and intentionally rejected after incompatible query/sort changes.\n- GitHub Actions do not run scale benchmarks; performance evidence and regression checks run locally to avoid hosted-runner consumption.\n\n## Evidence and implementation lineage\n\n- pm-mi2x: deterministic local scale generator, measurements, reports, and budgets.\n- pm-801d: derived index substrate and read-path adoption.\n- pm-dfg0: cursor and bounded-output adoption.\n- pm-0qg5: format-versioned item/history/lock fan-out.\n- pm-o79o: history and Git growth automation/guidance.\n- pm-lvyd / pm-2muu / pm-114v: claim throughput and lock semantics."
